					<head>Liturgy</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/n80040114" rend="visible">
						<summary>A festival prayer book.</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he"/>
						<msItem n="0" rend="visible" class="lccn.loc.gov/n80040114">
							<locus from="1r" to="140v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Maḥzor</title>
							<title xml:lang="he">מחזור</title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="2r" to="15v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Seder Taḥanunim</title>
							<note>
								<p>In agreement with the Italian prayer books. The Psalms were written in a contemporary semi-cursive script in the margin.</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="15v" to="34r"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Services for Rosh ha-Shanah</title>
							<filiation>Ct the poetical pieces contained in Add MS 19945, V, <ref target="Margoliouth_1965" type="number">627</ref>.</filiation>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="34r" to="137v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Services for Yom Kipur</title>
							<filiation>Cf the contents of Add MS 19945, VI, <ref target="Margoliouth_1965" type="number">627</ref>.</filiation>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="137v" to="139v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Additional pieces</title>
							<note>
								<p>Given in somewhat later handwriting.</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of the 15th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<support>Parchment.</support>
								<extent>140 folios <dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>280</height>
										<width>200</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>165</height>
										<width>110</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>140 folios (+ 1 unfoliated modern paper flyleaf at the beginning and at the end). Folio 1 is a paper flyleaf.</p>
									<p>Hebrew foliation has been preserved.</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>14 quires of 10 leaves each (folios 2-140), marked with catchwords and signatures at the end.</p>
								</collation>
								<condition>
									<p>Defective at the beginning.</p>
								</condition>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="1" ruledLines="26" writtenLines="26">
									<p>Uniform layout.</p>
									<p>Visible hard-point ruling and pricking.</p>
									<p>Initial words written in larger characters.</p>
									<p>Hair side and flesh side are distinguishable.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="1">
							<summary>Italian square and semi-cursive script of the 15th century. Punctuated.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="major"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>Censored by <name type="person" role="censor">Dominico Irosolomitano</name>, Italian censor (active 1585-1624): inscribed with his name, 1598 (folio 139v); see <ref target="Popper_1969" type="page">61</ref>, and appendix § 62-74.
</p>
							<p>Censored by <name type="person" role="censor">Giovanni Domenico Carretto</name>, Italian censor (active 1600-1624): inscribed with his name, 1623 (folio 139v); see <ref target="Popper_1969" type="page">100-101</ref>William Popper, The Censorship of Hebrew Books (New York: KTAV Publishing House, 1969).</p>
							<p>A note relating to berit milah, mentioning Rafa᾿el ben Shemu᾿el of Modena, undated: folio 140v. </p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p>BM in-house.</p>
								<p>Spine: 'Liturgies. Hebrew. Brit. Mus. Harl. MS. 5682.'</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
					</physDesc>
					<history rend="visible">
						<origin notBefore="1400" notAfter="1499"/>
						<provenance>
							<p>
								<name type="place">Italy</name>
							</p>
						</provenance>
						<acquisition>
							<date>1753</date>
							<p>The Harley Collection, formed by <name type="person" role="owner">Robert Harley</name> (b. 1661, d. 1724), 1st earl of Oxford and Mortimer, politician, and <name type="person" role="owner">Edward Harley</name> (b. 1689, d. 1741), 2nd earl of Oxford and Mortimer, book collector and patron of the arts: inscribed as usual by their librarian, <name type="person">Humfrey Wanley</name>, ‘18 die Januarii, A.D. 1723/4’ (folio 2r).
Edward Harley bequeathed the library to his widow, <name type="person" role="owner">Henrietta Cavendish, née Holles</name> (b. 1694, d. 1755) during her lifetime and thereafter to their daughter, <name type="person" role="owner">Margaret Cavendish Bentinck</name> (b. 1715, d. 1785), duchess of Portland; the manuscripts were sold by the Countess and the Duchess in <date calendar="Gregorian">1753</date> to the nation for £10,000 (a fraction of their contemporary value) under the Act of Parliament that also established the British Museum; the Harley manuscripts form one of the foundation collections of the British Library.</p>
						</acquisition>
					</history>
